		<profileDesc>
			<abstract>
				<p>A correlation-based learning rule at the spike level is formulated, mathematically analyzed, and compared to learning in a firing-rate description. A differential equation for the learning dynamics is derived under the assumption that the time scales of learning and spiking can be separated. For a linear Poissonian neuron model which receives time-dependent stochastic input we show that spike correlations on a millisecond time scale play indeed a role. Correlations between input and output spikes tend to stabilize structure formation, provided that the form of the learning window is in accordance with Hebb&apos;s principle. Conditions for an intrinsic nor-malization of the average synaptic weight are discussed.</p>
			</abstract>
